Good — next entry is **FB-228**. I have everything I need for the complete diagnosis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

The bug is a **sticky nav clipped inside an overflow-x scroll container**.

Here's the exact DOM chain:

```
<div class={siteWrapper}>            ← flex column, full height
  <nav class={nav}>                  ← position: sticky; top: 0  ← THE PROBLEM
  <div class={contentArea}>          ← overflow-x: auto  (below sm on pointer:fine)
    <div class={contentAreaInner}>   ← min-width: 672px
```

At viewports narrower than 320px (or any viewport below 672px on a pointer-fine device), `contentArea` gets `overflow-x: auto`. This is correct for the content. The issue is that `overflow-x: auto` on **any ancestor** implicitly clips `position: sticky` children — because the sticky element's scroll container becomes that overflowing ancestor, not the viewport. More critically: the `nav` is a **flex sibling** of `contentArea` inside `siteWrapper`, and `siteWrapper` has no explicit `overflow` value, so the browser's internal reflow can cause the document root to clip horizontal overflow. At very narrow viewports (< 320px), if anything escapes the nav's fluid width (e.g., the flex gap between logo and tagline, the `navInner`'s `padding: spacer-2x` summing wider than the viewport), the nav overflows but the page root has no horizontal scroll mechanism — it just clips.

The specific failure mode: `navInner` has `max-width: $elan-container-wide` and `margin: 0 auto` — it's fluid. But the `nav` element itself has no `min-width` constraint and is supposed to be 100% viewport-wide. At < 320px the nav's content can extend rightward beyond the viewport, and because neither `html`, `body`, nor `siteWrapper` allow horizontal scroll, it's invisibly clipped.

**Root cause: AP-067** — a `min-width` floor was previously placed on the root wrapper (now removed per FB-149), but the *inverse* version of this error was introduced: the `contentArea`'s `overflow-x: auto` containment is correct in isolation, but neither `html` nor `body` has `overflow-x: auto` to permit viewport-level horizontal scroll for any content that escapes the nav's natural width at extreme narrowness. The nav has no floor of its own and no affordance for scrolling its own overflowing content.

The fix is a two-part surgical correction: (1) the `nav` needs `overflow-x: auto` on its own (not `hidden`) so nav contents that exceed the actual viewport width at < 320px become scrollable within the nav band, and (2) the rule that **nothing touches `html`/`body`/`siteWrapper` with any `overflow` or `min-width` constraint** needs to be hardened in AP-067.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome** — and its inverse: any `overflow` property placed on a root-level ancestor (including omitting `overflow-x: auto` from the sticky nav itself) that contains functional chrome either clips it or traps it in a scroll context that the user cannot access.

The nav uses `position: sticky`, which means it sticks *within its scroll container*. Its scroll container is `siteWrapper` (the direct parent). `siteWrapper` has no `overflow` set, so by default the nav sticks within the viewport — which is correct. But at sub-320px widths, the nav's intrinsic content width (logo + gap + tagline with padding) can exceed the viewport. Since `siteWrapper` has no `overflow-x: auto`, the nav right edge is clipped with no scroll handle. The nav doesn't need a `min-width` floor — it needs to be *independently scrollable* when it overflows.

---

## Fix

### 1. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

Add `overflow-x: auto` to `.nav` so the nav band itself scrolls horizontally when its content exceeds the viewport width, rather than clipping silently. This is the minimum-footprint fix: it only activates when nav content genuinely overflows (i.e., at astronomically narrow widths < ~280px), and it does not affect the sticky behaviour, which is governed by the nav's position within `siteWrapper`.

```scss
// BEFORE
.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  ...
}
```

```scss
// AFTER — add overflow-x: auto
.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  // Never clip nav contents at extreme narrow viewports. overflow-x: auto
  // lets the nav band scroll horizontally when its own content (logo + tagline)
  // exceeds the actual viewport width. This only activates below ~280px.
  // Do NOT use overflow-x: hidden here — that would silently clip menu items
  // on the right and give the user no recovery path. See AP-067.
  overflow-x: auto;

  &::after { ... } // unchanged
}
```

### 2. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`

Add a protective comment to the `siteWrapper` block to make the rule machine-enforceable, and add an explicit `overflow-x: clip` guard note. **Important:** do not add any `overflow` property to `siteWrapper` — doing so would break the nav's sticky behaviour (an overflow-creating ancestor becomes the scroll container, severing the sticky relationship with the viewport). The existing code is correct; the comment just needs to be a hard guardrail:

```scss
// BEFORE
.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  // ... CSS custom property overrides
}
```

```scss
// AFTER — add AP-067 guardrail comment
.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;

  // ── AP-067 GUARDRAIL ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // NEVER add min-width, overflow-x: hidden, or overflow-x: clip to this
  // element. It is the scroll container for the sticky Navigation. Any
  // overflow property here would (a) sever the nav's sticky/viewport
  // relationship and (b) clip nav contents at narrow viewports with no
  // recovery path. The min-width floor lives on .contentAreaInner only.
  // See AP-067, FB-147, FB-149, FB-228.

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  // ... rest of CSS custom property overrides unchanged
}
```

### 3. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — update AP-067

Add the **inverse failure mode** (nav clipping without scroll) to the existing AP-067 entry, and reference FB-228:

```markdown
<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger (original):** Applying `min-width` to a root wrapper (e.g. `siteWrapper`, `body`, `html`) that contains both functional chrome (Navigation, Footer) and page content — this causes the nav to become wider than the viewport, with no way for the user to scroll to right-clipped menu items (FB-147, FB-149).

**Trigger (inverse — FB-228):** *Not* providing an independent `overflow-x: auto` escape on the Navigation element itself. When the nav's content (logo + gap + tagline + padding) exceeds the actual viewport width at extreme narrowness (< ~280px), and neither `html`/`body`/`siteWrapper` allows horizontal scroll, the right edge of the nav is silently clipped. The user can hover to reveal items but has no scroll handle to reach them.

**Why it's wrong:** Functional chrome must always be reachable. Clipping it — in either direction (too wide a min-width forcing the page to clip, or too-narrow a viewport without a nav-level scroll affordance) — breaks the primary navigation contract. The user can literally see content but cannot reach it.

**Correct alternative:**

1. **Root wrapper (`siteWrapper`):** No `min-width`, no `overflow-x` of any kind. It is the sticky scroll container. Touching its overflow severs `position: sticky`.
2. **Content area (`contentArea`):** `overflow-x: auto` + `min-width: 0`. This contains horizontal scroll to the *content region only*, leaving the nav unaffected.
3. **Content inner (`contentAreaInner`):** The `min-width` floor (e.g. `$elan-bp-sm`) lives here and only here.
4. **Navigation (`.nav`):** `overflow-x: auto`. This gives the nav band its own horizontal scroll handle at extreme narrowness (< ~280px viewport). Never `overflow-x: hidden` on the nav — that recreates the clipping problem.

**The structural invariant:** Every element that contains functional chrome the user must be able to interact with must either (a) be fluid and never overflow, or (b) have its own `overflow-x: auto` so overflow is reachable. Silent clipping (`hidden`, no scroll, or a parent `min-width` with no scroll affordance) is always wrong for interactive chrome.

**Related:** FB-147, FB-149, FB-228. See `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10.
```

### 4. `docs/design/responsive.md` — add §6.10 Nav scroll invariant

Append to the existing §6.10 block:

```markdown
**Nav scroll invariant (FB-228):** The Navigation element itself must carry
`overflow-x: auto`. At extreme viewport narrowness (< ~280px), nav content
(logo + tagline + padding) can exceed the actual viewport width. Without a
nav-level scroll handle, the right edge clips silently — the user can hover to
see items but cannot reach them. `overflow-x: auto` on `.nav` provides the
escape hatch. Never use `overflow-x: hidden` on the nav element.
```

### 5. `docs/design-feedback-log.md` — append FB-228 (newest first)

```markdown
#### FB-228: "On viewports narrower than 320px, nav is clipped on the right — no scroll"

**UX Intent:** Functional chrome must always be reachable at any viewport width.
A visible-but-unreachable nav item is worse than a fully hidden one.

**Root Cause:** `position: sticky` nav had no `overflow-x` property. At sub-280px
viewports, nav content (logo + padding + tagline) exceeds the actual viewport width.
Neither `html`/`body`/`siteWrapper` provides horizontal scroll (correctly — touching
those breaks sticky). The nav itself had no escape hatch, so content was silently
clipped with no scroll handle. This is the *inverse* of AP-067 (too-wide a root
min-width); both failure modes leave functional chrome unreachable.

**Resolution:** Added `overflow-x: auto` to `.nav` in `Navigation.module.scss`.
Added AP-067 guardrail comment to `.siteWrapper` in `layout.module.scss`.
AP-067 updated with the inverse trigger. `responsive.md` §6.10 extended with
the Nav scroll invariant.

**Pattern extracted → `design-anti-patterns.md` AP-067 (amended): inverse trigger added.**
**Cross-ref → `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10.**
```

---

## Principle

**AP-067 — Structural invariant for functional chrome:** Every element containing interactive chrome must either (a) be naturally fluid and never overflow, or (b) have its own `overflow-x: auto` so that overflow *is reachable*. Silent clipping — whether caused by a `min-width` floor on a root wrapper pushing content wider than the viewport with no scroll, or by the absence of a scroll handle on the nav element itself — always violates the navigation contract. The cascade is: `siteWrapper` touches nothing (sticky context), `contentArea` owns `overflow-x: auto` (page scroll), `contentAreaInner` owns the `min-width` floor (desktop composition), and `nav` owns its own `overflow-x: auto` (nav-band scroll). Each layer owns exactly one concern and never borrows from another.

